<p>These calculators work for both needle knitting or loom knitting project=
s.<strong>&nbsp;Use them right here on the website.  (Be sure to bookmark t=
his page for later.) </strong> &nbsp; </p>



<p>It=E2=80=99s simple.  Enter some details about your project and yarn.  M=
y own personal math elves will crunch the numbers for you.&nbsp; How easy i=
s that?</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">What can I calculate?</h3>



<p>You can calculate the following for your project (links take you directl=
y to the calculator):</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><a href=3D"https://www.goodknitkisses.com/interactive-knitting-calculat=
or/#caston"><strong>Cast On Calculator</strong></a><strong> </strong>=E2=80=
=93 Figure the number of stitches to cast on for a project.</li>



<li><a href=3D"https://www.goodknitkisses.com/interactive-knitting-calculat=
or/#rowcount"><strong>Row Count Calculator</strong></a> =E2=80=93 Figure th=
e number of rows needed to get to your desired length.</li>



<li><a href=3D"https://www.goodknitkisses.com/interactive-knitting-calculat=
or/#yardage"><strong>Yardage Calculator</strong></a> =E2=80=93 Figure out a=
bout how much yarn you will need for your project.</li>
</ul>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">What do I need to use the calculators?</h3>



<p><strong>For Cast On or Row Count:</strong></p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>A gauge swatch (more about that below)</li>



<li>A ruler or tape measure (you can measure in inches or centimeters)</li>



<li>The width and length you want your finished project to be.&nbsp; (You c=
an find this on the pattern you=E2=80=99re using or you can enter the measu=
rements you want to have if you=E2=80=99re not using a pattern.)</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>For Yardage Calculator:</strong></p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>The yarn label from your yarn. (If you lost the label, you can look up =
the details in the yarn database at <a href=3D"https://www.ravelry.com/yarn=
s" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">Ravelry.com</a>.)</li>



<li>A postage or kitchen scale that can weigh small amounts (grams or ounce=
s)</li>
</ul>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Making a Gauge Swatch</h3>



<p>The interactive knitting calculators below use the measurements off a ga=
uge swatch.&nbsp; A gauge swatch is a small (usually a 6=E2=80=B3 x 6=E2=80=
=B3) square knit in the stitch you plan to use for your project.&nbsp; </p>



<p data-slot-rendered-content=3D"true">Start by knitting a small square <i>=
in the yarn for your project</i>.&nbsp; If you are planning an ewrap scarf =
make sure you use ewrap for your swatch.&nbsp; For more detailed help, chec=
k out this blog post, <a href=3D"https://www.goodknitkisses.com/Resources/s=
watching-or-making-a-gauge-swatch/">Swatching or Making a Gauge Swatch</a>.=
</p>
